# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nanoid-ids
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] A tiny, secure, URL-friendly, unique string ID generator for JavaScript.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Made at **Evil Martians**, product consulting for **developer tools**.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Nano ID is quite comparable to UUID v4 (random-based).
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Nano ID code is **4 times smaller** than `uuid/v4` package: 118 bytes instead of 423.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Test configuration: Framework 13 7840U, Fedora 39, Node.js 21.6.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Nano ID 5 works with ESM projects (with `import`) in tests or Node.js scripts.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] JSR is a replacement for npm with open governance and active development (in contrast to npm).
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] You can use it in Node.js, Deno, Bun, etc.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] For Deno install it by `deno add jsr:@sitnik/nanoid` or import from `jsr:@sitnik/nanoid`.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] For quick hacks, you can load Nano ID from CDN.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Though, it is not recommended to be used in production because of the lower loading performance.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Nano ID has 2 APIs: normal and non-secure.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] By default, Nano ID uses URL-friendly symbols (`A-Za-z0-9_-`) and returns an ID with 21 characters (to have a collision probability similar to UUID v4).
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] The safe and easiest way to use Nano ID.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] In rare cases could block CPU from other work while noise collection for hardware random generator.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] If you want to reduce the ID size (and increase collisions probability), you can pass the size as an argument.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Don’t forget to check the safety of your ID size in our ID collision probability calculator.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] You can also use a custom alphabet or a random generator.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] By default, Nano ID uses hardware random bytes generation for security and low collision probability.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] If you are not so concerned with security, you can use it for environments without hardware random generators.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] `customAlphabet` returns a function that allows you to create `nanoid` with your own alphabet and ID size.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Check the safety of your custom alphabet and ID size in our ID collision probability calculator.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] For more alphabets, check out the options in `nanoid-dictionary`.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Alphabet must contain 256 symbols or less.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Otherwise, the security of the internal generator algorithm is not guaranteed.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] `customRandom` allows you to create a `nanoid` and replace alphabet and the default random bytes generator.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] `random` callback must accept the array size and return an array with random numbers.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] If you want to use the same URL-friendly symbols with `customRandom`, you can get the default alphabet using the `urlAlphabet`.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Note, that between Nano ID versions we may change random generator call sequence.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] If you are using seed-based generators, we do not guarantee the same result.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] There’s no correct way to use Nano ID for React `key` prop since it should be consistent among renders.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] You should rather try to reach for stable ID inside your list item.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] In case you just need random IDs to link elements like labels and input fields together, `useId` is recommended.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] React Native does not have built-in random generator.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] The following polyfill works for plain React Native and Expo starting with `39.x`.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] In PouchDB and CouchDB, IDs can’t start with an underscore `_`.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] A prefix is required to prevent this issue, as Nano ID might use a `_` at the start of the ID by default.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] You can get unique ID in terminal by calling `npx nanoid`.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] You do not need Nano ID to be installed anywhere.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] Nano ID allows casting generated strings into opaque strings in TypeScript.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] You can use these ports to have the same ID generator on the client and server side.
[src:nanoid-ids/ai-nanoid] For other environments, CLI is available to generate IDs from a command line.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] When comparing the original data to the resulting encoded data, Base64 encoding increases the size by 33% plus about 4% additional if inserting line breaks for typical line length.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The earliest uses of this encoding were for dial-up communication between systems running the same operating system – for example, uuencode for UNIX and BinHex for the TRS-80 (later adapted for the Macintosh) – and could therefore make more assumptions about what characters were safe to use.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] For instance, uuencode uses uppercase letters, digits, and many punctuation characters, but no lowercase.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Encoding an attachment as Base64 before sending, and then decoding when received, assures older SMTP servers correctly transmit messages with attached binary information.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] For example, to include the data of an image in a script to avoid depending on external files.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] format, some viewers can interpret Base64 when used for embedded elements, such as raster images inside SVG files.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] can use Base64 to represent file contents.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] URIs, instead of being supplied in separate files.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] functionality, especially in cases where the information doesn't warrant being permanently saved or when information must be quickly sent between a wide variety of different, potentially incompatible programs.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] , which contains binary data, is sometimes stored as Base64 since it is more likely that a QR code reader accurately decodes text than binary data.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Also, some devices more readily save text from a QR code than potentially malicious binary data.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The set of characters used to represent the values for each base-64 digit (value from 0 to 63) differs slightly between the variations of Base64.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The general strategy is to use printable characters that are common to most character encodings.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] This tends to result in data remaining unchanged as it moves through information systems, such as email, that were traditionally not 8-bit clean.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Many variants use `+` and `/` for the last two.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Per RFC 4648 §4, the following table lists the characters used for each numeric value.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Base64URL encoding replaces `+` with `-` and `/` with `_` to make the encoded string HTTP-safe and avoid the need for escaping.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] To simplify explanation, the example below uses plain text for input.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] While this is done in practice, a much more common use is encoding images and other data that are normally not representable with plain text, and the result then represents the data in a printable text format.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Each input sequence of 6 bits (which can encode 26 = 64 values) is mapped to a Base64 alphabet letter.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Therefore, Base64 encoding results in four characters for each three input bytes.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Which encodes the string `TWFu` (per ASCII or similar).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The following table shows how input is encoded.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] For example, the letter 'M' has the value `77` (per ASCII and similar).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The first 6 bits of the value is `010011` or 19 decimal which maps to Base64 letter 'T' which has a value `84` (per ASCII and similar).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] If the input consists of a number of bytes that is 2 more than a multiple of 3 (e.g.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] 'M', 'a'), then the last 2 bytes (16 bits) are encoded in 3 Base64 digits (18 bits).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The two least significant bits of the last content-bearing 6-bit block are treated as zero for encoding and discarded for decoding (along with the trailing `=` padding character).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] If the input consists of a number of bytes that is 1 more than a multiple of 3 (e.g.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] 'M'), then the last 8 bits are represented in 2 Base64 digits (12 bits).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] When decoding, each sequence of four encoded characters is converted to three output bytes, but with a single padding character the final 4 characters decode to only two bytes, or with two padding characters, the final 4 characters decode to a single byte.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Another way to interpret the padding character is to consider it as an instruction to discard 2 trailing bits from the bit string each time a `=` is encountered.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] For example, when bGlnaHQgdw== is decoded, we convert each character (except the trailing occurrences of `=`) into their corresponding 6-bit representation, and then discard 2 trailing bits for the first `=` and another 2 trailing bits for the other `=`.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] In this instance, we would get 6 bits from the `d`, and another 6 bits from the `w` for a bit string of length 12, but since we remove 2 bits for each `=` (for a total of 4 bits), the `dw==` ends up producing 8 bits (1 byte) when decoded.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Use of the padding character in encoded text is not essential for decoding.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The number of missing bytes can be inferred from the length of the encoded text.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] In some variants, the padding character is mandatory, while for others it is not used.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Notably, when concatenating Base64 encoded strings, then use of padding characters is *required* during encoding to avoid ambiguity when decoding.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Without padding, after decoding each sequence of 4 encoded characters, there may be 2 or 3 encoded characters left over.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] A single remaining encoded character is not possible because a single Base64 character only contains 6 bits, and 8 bits are required to create a byte.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The first Base64 character contributes 6 bits, and the second Base64 character contributes its first 2 bits to finish filling the byte.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The following table demonstrates decoding encoded strings that have 2, 3 or no left-over characters.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Decoding without padding is not performed consistently among decoders - some decoders require padding while other decoders infer the correct amount of padding from the encoded input string.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] In addition, allowing padless decoding by definition allows one list of strings written in some particular order to decode into several possible different output strings rather than only one possible output string, which can be a security risk due to the unpredictable and/or unexpected decoding.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Variations of Base64 differ in the alphabet used and structural aspects like maximum line length.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The most commonly used alphabet is that described by RFC 4648 and most variations only differ in the last two letters used.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The following table describes more commonly used encodings that are specified by an RFC.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] RFC 4648 describes a various encodings including Base64, and it discusses the use of line feeds in encoded data, the use of padding in encoded data, the use of non-alphabet characters in encoded data, use of different encoding alphabets, and canonical encodings.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The variant that it calls *Base 64 Encoding* and *base64* is intended for general-use.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The RFC also specifies a second Base64 encoding that it calls *Base 64 Encoding with URL and Filename Safe Alphabet* that is intended for representing relatively long identifying information.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] For example, a database persistence framework for Java objects might use Base64 encoding to encode a relatively large unique id (generally 128-bit UUIDs) as a string for use as an HTTP parameter in an HTTP form or an HTTP GET URL.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Also, many applications need to encode binary data in a way that is convenient for inclusion in a URL, including in hidden web form fields, and Base64 is a convenient encoding to render them in a compact way.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Using standard Base64 in a URL requires encoding the `+`, `/` and `=` characters as special percent-encoded hexadecimal sequences (`+` becomes `%2B`, `/` becomes `%2F` and `=` becomes `%3D`), which makes the string longer and harder to read.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Using a different alphabet allows for encoding as Base64 without requiring this extra markup.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Typically, `+` and `/` are replaced by `-` and `_`, respectively, so that using URL encoders/decoders is no longer necessary and has no effect on the length of the encoded value, leaving the same encoded form intact for use in relational databases, web forms, and object identifiers in general.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] A popular site to make use of such is YouTube.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Some variants allow or require omitting the padding `=` signs to avoid them being confused with field separators, or require that any such padding be percent-encoded.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Some libraries encode `=` as `.`, potentially exposing applications to relative path attacks when a folder name is encoded from user data.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] RFC 3548, entitled *The Base16, Base32, and Base64 Data Encodings*, is an informational (non-normative) memo that attempts to unify the RFC 1421 and RFC 2045 specifications of Base64 encodings, alternative-alphabet encodings, and the Base32 (which is seldom used) and Base16 encodings.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The MIME (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions) specification lists Base64 as one of two binary-to-text encoding schemes (the other being quoted-printable).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] MIME's Base64 encoding is based on that of the RFC 1421 version of PEM: it uses the same 64-character alphabet and encoding mechanism as PEM and uses the `=` symbol for output padding in the same way, as described at RFC 2045.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] MIME does not specify a fixed length for Base64-encoded lines, but it does specify a maximum line length of 76 characters.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Additionally, it specifies that any character outside the standard set of 64 encoding characters (for example CRLF sequences), must be ignored by a compliant decoder, although most implementations use a CR/LF newline pair to delimit encoded lines.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Thus, the actual length of MIME-compliant Base64-encoded binary data is usually about 137% of the original data length (4⁄3×78⁄76), though for very short messages the overhead can be much higher due to the overhead of the headers.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Very roughly, the final size of Base64-encoded binary data is equal to 1.37 times the original data size + 814 bytes (for headers).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The first known standardized use of the encoding now called MIME Base64 was in the Privacy-Enhanced Mail (PEM) protocol, proposed by RFC 989 in 1987.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] PEM defines a "printable encoding" scheme that uses Base64 encoding to transform an arbitrary sequence of bytes to a format that can be expressed in short lines of 6-bit characters, as required by transfer protocols such as SMTP.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The current version of PEM (specified in RFC 1421) uses a 64-character alphabet consisting of upper- and lower-case Roman letters (`A`–`Z`, `a`–`z`), the numerals (`0`–`9`), and the `+` and `/` symbols.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The `=` symbol is also used as a padding suffix.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The original specification, RFC 989, additionally used the `*` symbol to delimit encoded but unencrypted data within the output stream.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] To convert data to PEM printable encoding, the first byte is placed in the most significant eight bits of a 24-bit buffer, the next in the middle eight, and the third in the least significant eight bits.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] If there are fewer than three bytes left to encode (or in total), the remaining buffer bits will be zero.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The buffer is then used, six bits at a time, most significant first, as indices into the string: "`ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789+/`", and the indicated character is output.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The process is repeated on the remaining data until fewer than four bytes remain.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] If three bytes remain, they are processed normally.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] If fewer than three bytes (24 bits) are remaining to encode, the input data is right-padded with zero bits to form an integral multiple of six bits.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] After encoding the non-padded data, if two bytes of the 24-bit buffer are padded-zeros, two `=` characters are appended to the output; if one byte of the 24-bit buffer is filled with padded-zeros, one `=` character is appended.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] This signals the decoder that the zero bits added due to padding should be excluded from the reconstructed data.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] This also guarantees that the encoded output length is a multiple of 4 bytes.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] PEM requires that all encoded lines consist of exactly 64 printable characters, with the exception of the last line, which may contain fewer printable characters.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Lines are delimited by whitespace characters according to local (platform-specific) conventions.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] UTF-7, described first in RFC 1642, which was later superseded by RFC 2152, introduced a system called *modified Base64*.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] This data encoding scheme is used to encode UTF-16 as ASCII characters for use in 7-bit transports such as SMTP.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] It is a variant of the Base64 encoding used in MIME.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The "Modified Base64" alphabet consists of the MIME Base64 alphabet, but does not use the "`=`" padding character.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] UTF-7 is intended for use in mail headers (defined in RFC 2047), and the "`=`" character is reserved in that context as the escape character for "quoted-printable" encoding.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Modified Base64 simply omits the padding and ends immediately after the last Base64 digit containing useful bits leaving up to three unused bits in the last Base64 digit.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] OpenPGP, described in RFC 9580, specifies "ASCII armor", which is identical to the "Base64" encoding described by MIME, with the addition of an optional 24-bit CRC.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The checksum is calculated on the input data before encoding; the checksum is then encoded with the same Base64 algorithm and, prefixed by the "`=`" symbol as the separator, appended to the encoded output data.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The `atob()` and `btoa()` JavaScript methods, defined in the HTML5 draft specification, provide Base64 encoding and decoding functionality to web pages.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] The `btoa()` method outputs padding characters, but these are optional in the input of the `atob()` method.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Example: Encoding of the beginning of a GIF file: `btoa("GIF89a")` ↦ `"R0lGODlh"`.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Several variants use alphabets similar to the common variants, but in a different order.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] An advantage over RFC 4648 is that sorting encoded ASCII data results in the same order as sorting the plain ASCII data.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] 5.5 standard for genealogical data interchange encodes multimedia files in its text-line hierarchical file format.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Some variants use a Base64 alphabet that is significantly different from the alphabets used in the most common Base64 variants (like RFC 4648).
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Avoiding all lower-case letters was helpful, because many older printers only printed uppercase.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Using consecutive ASCII characters saved computing power, because it was only necessary to add 32, without requiring a lookup table.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Its use of most punctuation characters and the space character may limit its usefulness in some applications, such as those that use these characters as syntax.
[src:nanoid-ids/base64] Its alphabet includes additional punctuation characters.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] The **`Crypto.getRandomValues()`** method lets you get cryptographically strong random values.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] The array given as the parameter is filled with random numbers (random in its cryptographic meaning).
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] To guarantee enough performance, implementations are not using a truly random number generator, but they are using a pseudo-random number generator *seeded* with a value with enough entropy.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] The pseudo-random number generator algorithm (PRNG) may vary across user agents, but is suitable for cryptographic purposes.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] `getRandomValues()` is the only member of the `Crypto` interface which can be used from an insecure context.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] An integer-based `TypedArray`, that is one of: `Int8Array`, `Uint8Array`, `Uint8ClampedArray`, `Int16Array`, `Uint16Array`, `Int32Array`, `Uint32Array`, `BigInt64Array`, `BigUint64Array` (but **not** `Float16Array`, `Float32Array` nor `Float64Array`).
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] All elements in the array will be overwritten with random numbers.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] The same array passed as `typedArray` but with its contents replaced with the newly generated random numbers.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] Note that `typedArray` is modified in-place, and no copy is made.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] Thrown if the `byteLength` of `typedArray` exceeds 65,536.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] Prefer the `generateKey()` method for key generation, which is guaranteed to be running in a secure context.
[src:nanoid-ids/getrandomvalues] There is no minimum degree of entropy mandated by the Web Cryptography specification.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Various applications of randomness have led to the development of different methods for generating random data.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Some of these have existed since ancient times, including well-known examples like the rolling of dice, coin flipping, the shuffling of playing cards, the use of yarrow stalks (for divination) in the I Ching, as well as countless other techniques.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Because of the mechanical nature of these techniques, generating large quantities of sufficiently random numbers (important in statistics) required much work and time.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Thus, results would sometimes be collected and distributed as random number tables.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Several computational methods for pseudorandom number generation exist.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] All fall short of the goal of true randomness, although they may meet, with varying success, some of the statistical tests for randomness intended to measure how unpredictable their results are (that is, to what degree their patterns are discernible).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] This generally makes them unusable for applications such as cryptography.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] However, carefully designed *cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators* (CSPRNGS) also exist, with special features specifically designed for use in cryptography.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Random number generators have applications in gambling, statistical sampling, computer simulation, cryptography, completely randomized design, and other areas where producing an unpredictable result is desirable.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Generally, in applications having unpredictability as the paramount feature, such as in security applications, hardware generators are generally preferred over pseudorandom algorithms, where feasible.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Pseudorandom number generators are very useful in developing Monte Carlo-method simulations, as debugging is facilitated by the ability to run the same sequence of random numbers again by starting from the same *random seed*.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] They are also used in cryptography – so long as the *seed* is secret.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The sender and receiver can generate the same set of numbers automatically to use as keys.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The generation of pseudorandom numbers is an important and common task in computer programming.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] While cryptography and certain numerical algorithms require a very high degree of *apparent* randomness, many other operations only need a modest amount of unpredictability.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Some simple examples might be presenting a user with a "random quote of the day", or determining which way a computer-controlled adversary might move in a computer game.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Weaker forms of *randomness* are used in hash algorithms and in creating amortized searching and sorting algorithms.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Some applications that appear at first sight to be suitable for randomization are in fact not quite so simple.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] For instance, a system that "randomly" selects music tracks for a background music system must only *appear* random, and may even have ways to control the selection of music: a truly random system would have no restriction on the same item appearing two or three times in succession.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] There are two principal methods used to generate random numbers.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The first method measures some physical phenomenon that is expected to be random and then compensates for possible biases in the measurement process.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Example sources include measuring atmospheric noise, thermal noise, and other external electromagnetic and quantum phenomena.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] For example, cosmic background radiation or radioactive decay as measured over short timescales represent sources of natural entropy (as a measure of unpredictability or surprise of the number generation process).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The speed at which entropy can be obtained from natural sources is dependent on the underlying physical phenomena being measured.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Thus, sources of naturally occurring *true* entropy are said to be blocking – they are rate-limited until enough entropy is harvested to meet the demand.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] On some Unix-like systems, including most Linux distributions, the pseudo device file /dev/random will block until sufficient entropy is harvested from the environment.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Due to this blocking behavior, large bulk reads from /dev/random, such as filling a hard disk drive with random bits, can often be slow on systems that use this type of entropy source.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The second method uses computational algorithms that can produce long sequences of apparently random results, which are in fact completely determined by a shorter initial value, known as a seed value or key.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] As a result, the entire seemingly random sequence can be reproduced if the seed value is known.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] This type of random number generator is often called a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] This type of generator typically does not rely on sources of naturally occurring entropy, though it may be periodically seeded by natural sources.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] This generator type is non-blocking, so they are not rate-limited by an external event, making large bulk reads a possibility.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Standard cryptographic designs take a hybrid approach, using randomness harvested from natural sources to seed a cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generators (CSPRNGs).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Hardware random number generators generally produce only a limited number of random bits per second.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] In order to increase the available output data rate, they are often used to generate the "seed" for a faster PRNG.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] PRNG also helps with the noise source "anonymization" (whitening out the noise source identifying characteristics) and entropy extraction.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] With a proper PRNG algorithm selected (cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator, CSPRNG), the combination can satisfy the requirements of Federal Information Processing Standards and Common Criteria standards.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The earliest methods for generating random numbers, such as dice, coin flipping and roulette wheels, are still used today, mainly in games and gambling, as they tend to be too slow for most applications in statistics and cryptography.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Many natural phenomena generate low-level, statistically random "noise" signals, including thermal and shot noise, jitter and metastability of electronic circuits, Brownian motion, and atmospheric noise.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Researchers also used the photoelectric effect, involving a beam splitter, other quantum phenomena, and even nuclear decay (due to practical considerations the latter, as well as the atmospheric noise, is not viable except for fairly restricted applications or online distribution services).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] While "classical" (non-quantum) phenomena are not truly random, an unpredictable physical system is usually acceptable as a source of randomness, so the qualifiers "true" and "physical" are used interchangeably.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] A hardware random number generator is expected to output near-perfect random numbers ("full entropy").
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] For performance and security reasons, most random number generators use PRNGs in their construction (this architecture is actually mandated in the industrial standards like NIST SP 800-90A).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] A pseudorandom number generator (PRNG), also known as a deterministic random bit generator (DRBG), is an algorithm for generating a sequence of numbers whose properties approximate the properties of sequences of random numbers.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The PRNG-generated sequence is not truly random, because it is completely determined by an initial value, called the PRNG's *seed* (which may include truly random values).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Although sequences that are closer to truly random can be generated using hardware random number generators, *pseudorandom number generators* are important in practice for their speed in number generation and their reproducibility.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] PRNGs are central in applications such as simulations (e.g. for the Monte Carlo method), electronic games (e.g. for procedural generation), and cryptography.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Cryptographic applications require the output not to be predictable from earlier outputs, and more elaborate algorithms, which do not inherit the linearity of simpler PRNGs, are needed.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Good statistical properties are a central requirement for the output of a PRNG.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] In general, careful mathematical analysis is required to have any confidence that a PRNG generates numbers that are sufficiently close to random to suit the intended use.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Random number generation may also be performed by humans, in the form of collecting various inputs from end users and using them as a randomization source.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] However, most studies find that human subjects have some degree of non-randomness when attempting to produce a random sequence of e.g., digits or letters.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] They may alternate too much between choices when compared to a good random generator; thus, this approach is not widely used.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] However, for the very reason that humans perform poorly in this task, human random number generation can be used as a tool to gain insights into brain functions otherwise not accessible.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Even given a source of plausible random numbers (perhaps from a quantum mechanically based hardware generator), obtaining numbers which are completely unbiased takes care.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] In addition, behavior of these generators often changes with temperature, power supply voltage, the age of the device, or other outside interference.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Generated random numbers are sometimes subjected to statistical tests before use to ensure that the underlying source is still working, and then post-processed to improve their statistical properties.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] An example would be the TRNG9803 hardware random number generator, which uses an entropy measurement as a hardware test, and then post-processes the random sequence with a shift register stream cipher.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] It is generally hard to use statistical tests to validate the generated random numbers.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Wang and Nicol proposed a distance-based statistical testing technique that is used to identify the weaknesses of several random generators.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Li and Wang proposed a method of testing random numbers based on laser chaotic entropy sources using Brownian motion properties.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Statistical tests are also used to give confidence that the post-processed final output from a random number generator is truly unbiased, with numerous randomness test suites being developed.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Most random number generators natively work with integers or individual bits, so an extra step is required to arrive at the *canonical* uniform distribution between 0 and 1.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The implementation is not as trivial as dividing the integer by its maximum possible value.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The nature of floating-point math itself means there exists more precision the closer the number is to zero.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] This extra precision is usually not used due to the sheer number of bits required.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Rounding error in division may bias the result.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] At worst, a supposedly excluded bound may be drawn contrary to expectations based on real-number math.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The mainstream algorithm, used by OpenJDK, Rust, and NumPy, is described in a proposal for C++'s STL.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] It does not use the extra precision and suffers from bias only in the last bit due to rounding half to even.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Other numeric concerns are warranted when shifting this *canonical* uniform distribution to a different range.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] A proposed method for the Swift programming language claims to use the full precision everywhere.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Uniformly distributed integers are commonly used in algorithms such as the Fisher–Yates shuffle.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Again, a naive implementation may induce a modulo bias into the result, so more involved algorithms must be used.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] A method that nearly never performs division was described in 2018 by Daniel Lemire, with the current state-of-the-art being the arithmetic encoding-inspired 2021 "optimal algorithm" by Stephen Canon of Apple Inc.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Most 0 to 1 RNGs include 0 but exclude 1, while others include or exclude both.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Given a source of uniform random numbers, there are a couple of methods to create a new random source that corresponds to a probability density function.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] One method called the inversion method, involves integrating up to an area greater than or equal to the random number (which should be generated between 0 and 1 for proper distributions).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] A second method called the acceptance-rejection method, involves choosing an x and y value and testing whether the function of x is greater than the y value.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Otherwise, the x value is rejected and the algorithm tries again.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] As an example for rejection sampling, to generate a pair of statistically independent standard normally distributed random numbers (*x*, *y*), one may first generate the polar coordinates (*r*, *θ*), where *r*2~χ22 and *θ*~UNIFORM(0,2π) (see Box–Muller transform).
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The outputs of multiple independent RNGs can be combined (for example, using a bit-wise XOR operation) to provide a combined RNG at least as good as the best RNG used.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] This is referred to as software whitening.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Computational and hardware random number generators are sometimes combined to reflect the benefits of both kinds.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Computational random number generators can typically generate pseudorandom numbers much faster than physical generators, while physical generators can generate true randomness.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Some computations making use of a random number generator can be summarized as the computation of a total or average value, such as the computation of integrals by the Monte Carlo method.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] For such problems, it may be possible to find a more accurate solution by the use of so-called low-discrepancy sequences, also called quasirandom numbers.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Such sequences have a definite pattern that fills in gaps evenly, qualitatively speaking; a truly random sequence may, and usually does, leave larger gaps.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Since much cryptography depends on a cryptographically secure random number generator for key and cryptographic nonce generation, if a random number generator can be made predictable, it can be used as backdoor by an attacker to break the encryption.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] The NSA is reported to have inserted a backdoor into the NIST certified cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator Dual EC DRBG.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] If for example an SSL connection is created using this random number generator, then according to Matthew Green it would allow NSA to determine the state of the random number generator, and thereby eventually be able to read all data sent over the SSL connection.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] Even though it was apparent that Dual_EC_DRBG was a very poor and possibly backdoored pseudorandom number generator long before the NSA backdoor was confirmed in 2013, it had seen significant usage in practice until 2013, for example by the prominent security company RSA Security.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] There have subsequently been accusations that RSA Security knowingly inserted a NSA backdoor into its products, possibly as part of the Bullrun program.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] RSA has denied knowingly inserting a backdoor into its products.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] It has also been theorized that hardware RNGs could be secretly modified to have less entropy than stated, which would make encryption using the hardware RNG susceptible to attack.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] One such method that has been published works by modifying the dopant mask of the chip, which would be undetectable to optical reverse-engineering.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] For example, for random number generation in Linux, it is seen as unacceptable to use Intel's RDRAND hardware RNG without mixing in the RDRAND output with other sources of entropy to counteract any backdoors in the hardware RNG, especially after the revelation of the NSA Bullrun program.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] In 2010, a U.S. lottery draw was rigged by the information security director of the Multi-State Lottery Association (MUSL), who surreptitiously installed backdoor malware on the MUSL's secure RNG computer during routine maintenance.
[src:nanoid-ids/random-number-generation] During the hacks the man won a total amount of $16,500,000 over multiple years.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The **`SubtleCrypto`** interface of the Web Crypto API provides a number of low-level cryptographic functions.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The interface name includes the term "subtle" to indicate that many of its algorithms have subtle usage requirements, and hence that it must be used carefully in order to provide suitable security guarantees.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] An instance of `SubtleCrypto` is available as the `subtle` property of the `Crypto` interface, which in turn is available in windows through the `Window.crypto` property and in workers through the `WorkerGlobalScope.crypto` property.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Even assuming you use the basic cryptographic functions correctly, secure key management and overall security system design are extremely hard to get right, and are generally the domain of specialist security experts.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Errors in security system design and implementation can make the security of the system completely ineffective.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Please learn and experiment, but don't guarantee or imply the security of your work before an individual knowledgeable in this subject matter thoroughly reviews it.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The Crypto 101 Course can be a great place to start learning about the design and implementation of secure systems.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the encrypted data corresponding to the clear text, algorithm, and key given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the clear data corresponding to the encrypted text, algorithm, and key given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the signature corresponding to the text, algorithm, and key given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a boolean value indicating if the signature given as a parameter matches the text, algorithm, and key that are also given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a digest generated from the algorithm and text given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a newly-generated `CryptoKey`, for symmetrical algorithms, or a `CryptoKeyPair`, containing two newly generated keys, for asymmetrical algorithms.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] These will match the algorithm, usages, and extractability given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a newly generated `CryptoKey` derived from the master key and specific algorithm given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a newly generated buffer of pseudo-random bits derived from the master key and specific algorithm given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `CryptoKey` corresponding to the format, the algorithm, raw key data, usages, and extractability given as parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with the raw key data containing the key in the requested format.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a wrapped symmetric key for usage (transfer and storage) in insecure environments.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The wrapped key matches the format specified in the given parameters, and wrapping is done by the given wrapping key, using the specified algorithm.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a `CryptoKey` corresponding to the wrapped key given in the parameter.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] We can split the functions implemented by this API into two groups: cryptography functions and key management functions.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] These are the functions you can use to implement security features such as privacy and authentication in a system.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Except for `digest()`, all the cryptography functions in the API use cryptographic keys.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] In the `SubtleCrypto` API a cryptographic key is represented using a `CryptoKey` object.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] To perform operations like signing and encrypting, you pass a `CryptoKey` object into the `sign()` or `encrypt()` function.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The `generateKey()` and `deriveKey()` functions both create a new `CryptoKey` object.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The difference is that `generateKey()` will generate a new distinct key value each time you call it, while `deriveKey()` derives a key from some initial keying material.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] If you provide the same keying material to two separate calls to `deriveKey()`, you will get two `CryptoKey` objects that have the same underlying value.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] This is useful if, for example, you want to derive an encryption key from a password and later derive the same key from the same password to decrypt the data.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] To make keys available outside your app, you need to export the key, and that's what `exportKey()` is for.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] You can choose one of a number of export formats.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The inverse of `exportKey()` is `importKey()`.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] You can import keys from other systems, and support for standard formats like PKCS #8 and JSON Web Key helps you do this.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The `exportKey()` function exports the key in an unencrypted format.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] If the key is sensitive you should use `wrapKey()`, which exports the key and then encrypts it using another key; the API calls a "key-wrapping key".
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The inverse of `wrapKey()` is `unwrapKey()`, which decrypts then imports the key.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] `CryptoKey` is a serializable object, which allows keys to be stored and retrieved using standard web storage APIs.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The specification expects that most developers will use the IndexedDB API, storing `CryptoKey` objects against some key string identifier that is meaningful to the application, along with any other metadata it finds useful.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] This allows the storage and retrieval of the `CryptoKey` without having to expose its underlying key material to the application or the JavaScript environment.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] The cryptographic functions provided by the Web Crypto API can be performed by one or more different *cryptographic algorithms*: the `algorithm` argument to the function indicates which algorithm to use.
[src:nanoid-ids/subtlecrypto] Some algorithms need extra parameters: in these cases the `algorithm` argument is a dictionary object that includes the extra parameters.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] A **universally unique identifier** (**UUID**) is a 128-bit number used to identify information in computer systems.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The term **globally unique identifier** (**GUID**) is also used, typically in software created by Microsoft.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] When generated according to the standards, UUIDs are, for practical purposes, unique.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Their uniqueness does not depend on a central registration authority or coordination between the parties generating them, unlike most other numbering schemes.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] While the probability that a UUID will be duplicated is not zero, it is close enough to zero to be negligible.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, anyone can create large numbers of UUIDs and use them as identifiers with near certainty that they do not duplicate UUIDs that have been, or will be, created by others, with the only coordination required to achieve uniqueness being conformance with the UUID standards.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Information labeled with UUIDs by independent parties can therefore coexist in the same databases or channels, with a negligible probability of duplication.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Adoption of UUIDs is widespread, with many computing platforms providing support for generating them and for parsing their textual representation.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Apollo Computer used UUIDs in the Network Computing System (NCS), launched in 1987, with a design inspired by the 64-bit unique identifiers of Domain/OS, an earlier Apollo operating system.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Microsoft Windows platforms adopted the NCS (and later, the DCE) design as "Globally Unique Identifiers" (GUIDs) in the early nineties.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Somewhat later, the Open Software Foundation (OSF) used UUIDs in its Distributed Computing Environment (DCE), with a design partly based on the NCS UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This was documented in the DCE 1.1 RPC specification in 1996, and in the DCE 1.1 Authentication and Security Services specification, published in 1997.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] ISO/IEC documented the DCE design in 1996, in ISO/IEC 11578:1996 "Information technology – Open Systems Interconnection – Remote Procedure Call".
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In July 2005, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) published the Standards-Track RFC 4122., which also registered a URN namespace for UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The ITU had meanwhile also standardized UUIDs, based on the previous standards and early versions of RFC 4122, in ITU-T Rec.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This was technically equivalent to RFC 4122.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The current IETF specification is RFC 9562, a Proposed Standard published in May 2024.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This defined three new UUID versions (6–8) of the DCE variant.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The UUIDs currently in use are the DCE/IETF design, with provision for backwards compatibility with "legacy" Apollo NCS UUIDs and Microsoft GUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The authors of RFC 4122 were Paul Leach, Michael Mealling, and Rich Salz, and the authors of the initial 1997 Internet Draft were Leach and Salz.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Leach had been the Architect of Domain/OS, had continued at Apollo as a designer of NCS, and then, as a Microsoft Distinguished Architect, contributed to the design of OLE/COM/DCOM, carrying the concept of UUIDs to that project.Leach was also one of the authors of RFC 9562.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Salz was a member of the DCE team at the Open Software Foundation.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Apollo had merged in 1989 with Hewlett-Packard, a founding member of the OSF.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Former NCS team-members, having become HP employees, brought UUIDs to OSF DCE.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Mealling was a prominent IETF member, holding a seat on the Internet Engineering Steering Group, and was heavily involved in IETF work on URNs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 brought all these strands together.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The meaning of the bits is determined by the *variant*, of which three are defined.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Of these, the most common is variant 1, with the other variants being for backwards compatibility with previous formats or for future definition.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Variants 1 and 2 have "versions", which further define the interpretation of the UUID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The *variant* field is in a variable number of the most-significant bits of the ninth byte.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The OSF DCE and Microsoft COM/DCOM variants (1 & 2, respectively) have *versions*, indicated by the value of the high four bits of the seventh byte of the UUID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In textual representations of the UUID, this is the hex digit after the second hyphen.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Variant 0 Apollo NCS UUIDs do not have versions, being sub-typed via "address families" rather than versions.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562, which defined versions 6, 7, and 8 stated that variants other than the OSF DCE variant 1 were "out of scope" of the RFC, leaving it to Microsoft to define new versions for variant 2.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] However, versions 1 through 5, standardized in RFC 4122, are the same in the Microsoft variant, except for byte-ordering.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version 1 concatenates the 48-bit MAC address of the "node" (that is, the computer generating the UUID), with a 60-bit timestamp.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] On systems with 64-bit EUI-64 "MAC addresses", the least significant 48 bits are used.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] A 48-bit random number may also be used.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The timestamp is the number of 100-nanosecond intervals since midnight 15 October 1582 Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the date on which the Gregorian calendar was first adopted.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 states that the time value rolls over in A.D.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] 3409,depending on the algorithm used, which implies that the 60-bit timestamp is a signed quantity.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] However some software, such as the libuuid library, treats the timestamp as unsigned, putting the rollover time in A.D.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] A 13-bit or 14-bit "uniquifying" clock sequence extends the timestamp in order to handle cases where the processor clock does not advance fast enough, or where there are multiple processors and UUID generators per node.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] When UUIDs are generated faster than the system clock can advance, the lower bits of the timestamp and the clock sequence can be incremented to simulate greater precision and ensure uniqueness.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] With each version-1 UUID corresponding to a single point in space (the node) and time (intervals and clock sequence), the chance of two properly generated version-1 UUIDs being unintentionally the same is practically nil.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Since the time and clock sequence total 74 bits, 274 (1.8×1022, or 18 sextillion) version-1 UUIDs can be generated per node ID, at a maximal average rate of 163 billion per second per node ID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version 6 is the same as version 1 except for the order of the timestamp bits.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In version 6, timestamp bits are ordered from most significant to least significant.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This allows systems to sort version-6 UUIDs in order of creation simply by sorting them lexically.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] By reinstating the original NCS hi-lo byte order of the timestamp to enable sortability, version 6 is even more similar to "legacy" variant 0 NCS UUIDs than version 1.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFCs 4122 and 9562 reserve version 2 for "DCE security" UUIDs; but do not provide any details.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Many UUID implementations and libraries omit version 2.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] However, the specification of version-2 UUIDs is provided by the DCE 1.1 Authentication and Security Services specification.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version-2 UUIDs are similar to version 1, except that the least significant 8 bits of the clock sequence are replaced by a "local domain" number, and the least significant 32 bits of the 60-bit Gregorian timestamp are replaced by an integer identifier meaningful within the specified local domain.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] On POSIX systems, local-domain numbers 0 and 1 are for user ids (UIDs) and group ids (GIDs) respectively, and other local-domain numbers are site-defined.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] On non-POSIX systems, all local domain numbers are site-defined.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, version-2 UUIDs are a way to combine a 32-bit local, node-scoped identifier of a specified 8-bit type ("domain") with the identifier of the node and a Gregorian-origin timestamp, transforming the node-scoped identifier into one that is universally unique.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The tradeoff is that the timestamp is low-res in comparison to the timestamps in version 1, ticking only once once every 429.49 seconds, a little more than 7 minutes, quite different from the 100 nanosecond ticks in version 1.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version-3 and version-5 UUIDs are generated by hashing a namespace identifier and name.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version 3 uses MD5 as the hashing algorithm, and version 5 uses SHA-1.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This is useful when systems need deterministically to generate the same UUID based on a set of other names or identifiers, without coordination.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The namespace identifier is itself a UUID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC provides constant UUIDs to represent the namespaces for URLs, fully qualified domain names, object identifiers, and X.500 distinguished names; but any desired UUID may be used as a namespace designator.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] There is an IANA registry for additional namespace ids.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] To determine the version-3 UUID corresponding to a given namespace and name, the UUID of the namespace is transformed to a string of bytes, concatenated with the input name, then hashed with MD5, yielding 128 bits.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Then six or seven bits are replaced by fixed values, the four-bit version (e.g.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] 00112 for version 3), and the two- or three-bit UUID "variant" (e.g.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] 102 indicating an RFC 9562 UUIDs, or 1102 indicating a legacy Microsoft GUID).
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Since 6 or 7 bits are thus predetermined, only 121 or 122 bits contribute to the uniqueness of the UUID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version-5 UUIDs are similar, but SHA-1 is used instead of MD5.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Since SHA-1 generates 160-bit digests, the digest is truncated to 128 bits before the version and variant bits are replaced.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version-3 and version-5 UUIDs have the property that, given the version, the same namespace and name will map to the same UUID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] However, neither the namespace nor name can be determined from the UUID, even if one of them is specified, except by brute-force search.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 recommends version 5 (SHA-1) over version 3 (MD5).
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This is because it is believed that MD5 is more prone to collisions than SHA-1, though MD5 is somewhat faster.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC warns against use of UUIDs of any version as security capabilities.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] As in other UUIDs, four bits are used to indicate version 4, and two or three bits to indicate the variant (102 or 1102 for variants 1 and 2 respectively).
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, for variant 1 (that is, most UUIDs) a random version-4 UUID will have six predetermined variant and version bits, leaving 122 bits for the randomly generated part, for a total of 2122, or 5.3×1036 (5.3 undecillion) possible version-4, variant-1 UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] There are half as many possible version-4, variant 2 UUIDs (legacy GUIDs) because there is one less random bit available, three bits being consumed for the variant.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Version-7 UUIDs are intended as monotonically ascending, creation-time-ordered, lexically sortable keys in large databases and distributed systems, contributing to locality and performance.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] With version 7 as database keys, "new" records are inserted at the logical end of the key sequence, and records which are close in time are near each other in the key sequence.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This contrasts with the random version 4, which when used as database keys, are evenly and randomly dispersed across the key sequence, even when the underlying records are close in time, negatively affecting performance in many types of databases.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The 48-bit timestamps may be altered, fuzzed, or smeared for the sake of monotonicity and privacy, and it is explicitly stated that there is no requirement about how close a timestamp needs to be to the actual (Unix) time.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] But the intent is clear that the timestamps should be monontonic and approximate Unix time, and the RFC states that custom UUID version 8 should be used for timestamp-based designs that are not Unix time.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Unlike some other UUID versions, version-7 UUIDs do not incorporate MAC addresses, and can steer clear of the privacy issues associated with them.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In a custom UUID, the version is `8`, and the variant bits must be `10`, totaling 6 bits.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The remaining 122 bits are not specified.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] According to the RFC, version-8 UUIDs are intended for experimental and vendor-specific use cases.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC suggests, for example, that this version might be used for a name/hash-based identifier generated with a newer hashing function than those specified for UUID versions 3 (MD5) and 5 (SHA-1).
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The RFC also suggests that version 8 can be used for timestamp-based UUID designs that do not fit within versions 6 or 7, such as a different epoch.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] But version 8 is not restricted to such scenarios.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In essence, version-8 UUIDs are 122 opaque bits, combined with six version and variant bits, allowing them to be separated from other UUID forms.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Unlike other versions, the RFC does not mandate a specific bit layout or generation algorithm, and they are not to be assumed to be unique.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In addition, as with other UUID versions, there is no concept of version subtypes.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The uniqueness of the UUIDs based on network-card MAC addresses also depends on network-card manufacturers properly assigning unique MAC addresses to their cards which, like other manufacturing processes, is subject to error.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] MAC addresses also may come from sources other than network cards.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] For example, virtual machines receive a MAC address from a range that is configurable in the hypervisor, and some operating systems permit the end user to customise the MAC address, notably OpenWrt.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] When a device has an EUI-64 64-bit "MAC address", using the least significant 48 bits of it, as recommended by the RFC, may result in the node ID part of the UUID being duplicated.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, node IDs based on MAC addresses may not be globally unique.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Usage of the node's network card MAC address for the node ID does often mean that version-1, -2, and -6 UUIDs can be tracked back to the computer that created them.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Such UUIDs can be used to infer what kind of hardware is being used to generate the UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Documents can sometimes be traced to the computers where they were created or edited through UUIDs embedded into them by word processing software.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This privacy hole was used when locating the creator of the Melissa virus.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562 does allow the MAC address in a version-1, -2 or -6 UUID to be replaced by a random 48-bit node ID, either because the node does not have a MAC address, or because it is not desirable to include it.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In that case, the RFC requires that the least significant bit of the first octet of the node ID should be set to 1.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This corresponds to the multicast bit in MAC addresses, and setting it serves to differentiate UUIDs where the node ID is randomly generated from UUIDs based on MAC addresses from network cards, which typically have unicast MAC addresses.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Versions 1, 2, 6, and 7 are based on, and expose, the time when the UUID was generated, which often corresponds to the creation of a record, or an historical event.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] If associated with people or their activity, it may be possible to infer a person's age or the precise time of their activities from UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] It may be possible to determine from time-based monotonically-ascending UUIDs when a system went live, or what objects in a system are new or recently updated.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] If the identified objects represent product orders or user sign-ups, for example, it may be possible to determine user growth or sales volume over time from the UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, time-based UUIDs, if publicly visible, may leak personal or business information, raise privacy concerns, and facilitate unwanted data mining.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Concerning the time-ordering and sortability of UUIDs, version 1 and 2 start "in the middle" with the 32 low bits of the timestamp.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] These two versions, along with 3–5 and 8, do not sort lexically into time order.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The role of the timestamp in these UUID versions was not to make UUIDs readily orderable in time but rather to achieve universal uniqueness by fixing the generation in space and time.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Versions 6 and 7 prioritize the timestamp's role in database indexing, allowing for lexical sorting of records into chronological order.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] However, RFC 9562 provides significant implementation flexibility for version 7, defining a general framework rather than a rigid bit-layout for optional sub-millisecond timestamp precision, counters, and randomness.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The specification allows the 48-bit Unix timestamp to be adjusted or "fuzzed" to maintain monotonicity (ensuring IDs created in rapid succession always increase) or to enhance privacy.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Because the RFC does not define a strict maximum deviation from actual Unix time, different implementations may vary in how they balance chronological accuracy against these other requirements.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Consequently, the lexical sortability of versions 6 and 7 UUIDs is most consistent when generated by the same library or system.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Mixing UUIDs from different sources, or interleaving different versions and variants in a single database, can degrade the time-ordering and index locality that these versions were designed to provide.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 9562 does not mandate a minimum number of random bits for version 7; it allows the sub-millisecond precision and monotonicity counter fields to occupy the remainder of the 128-bit structure.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Consequently, collision resistance and guessability depend entirely on the specific implementation's allocation of these bits.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This is a "variant 0" NCS UUID with an address family of "0", defined in NCS as "unspecified or uninitialized".
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The Max UUID, sometimes also called the Omni UUID, is `FFFFFFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFFFFFFFFFF` (that is, all set bits).
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This is intended to be used for expressing "end of UUID list".
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 incorporated legacy NCS UUIDs as "variant 0" of the new format by overlapping the variant bits of the new format with the NCS Address Family field.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Since the highest address family value defined in NCS is 13 (hex 00 to 0D), the most significant bit in the variant octet is always 0 for extant NCS UUIDs, while this bit is 1 in the newer three IETF variants.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In effect, NCS address families 0–127 became the new "variant 0", while the numbering space of NCS address families 128–255, which was undefined in NCS, was rededicated to variant-1-to-3 IETF and Microsoft UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The result was that legacy NCS UUIDs and variant-1-to-3 UUIDs were separated and could coexist in the same databases, and on the same communication channels.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The legacy Apollo NCS UUID has the format described in the previous table.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The OSF DCE UUID variant is described in RFC 9562.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The Microsoft COM / DCOM UUID has its variant described in the Microsoft documentation, but for versions 1 to 5, is generally the same as the DCE variant, except for the extra variant bit and byte-ordering.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] (See next section.) Variant 2 does not have versions 6 to 8.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The interpretation of the various bit-blocks varies in variants 1 and 2 according to the "version".
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In variant 2, data_a, data_b, version|data_c are byte-swapped and variant|data_d and data_e are not byte-swapped.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Variant 1 UUIDs are sequentially encoded in big-endian.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In contrast, variant 2 UUIDs ("GUIDs"): historically used in Microsoft COM/OLE libraries, have a mixed-endian format, with the first three fields (corresponding to version-1 timestamp subfields) being little-endian, while the final two fields are emitted as big-endian arrays of bytes.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The example UUID above, if it were a variant 2 UUID, would be encoded on the wire as `33 22 11 00 55 44 77 66 88 99 aa bb cc dd ee ff`.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] All versions under variant 2 are emitted with this byte ordering, including versions not containing numeric fields, such as 3,4, and 5.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In most cases, UUIDs are represented as hexadecimal values separated by hyphens.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Most used is the 8-4-4-4-12 format, a string of 32 hexadecimal digits with four hyphens, `xxxxxxxx-xxxx-vxxx-wxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx`.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The hyphens separate the version-1 fields but the same format is commonly used for all versions.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Every hexadecimal digit represents 4 bits; `v` represents the version nibble; and the high-order one to three bits of `w` are the variant.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The Windows registry format is the same but wraps the UUID in `{}` braces.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The byte-ordering differences of variant 2 are applicable in binary storage or transmission on the wire, and do not affect the textual presentation of the UUID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Though they are still occasionally omitted, the format with hyphens was introduced with the newer variant system.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The first part is the time (time_high and time_low combined).
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The family field comes directly after the first dot, so in this case `0d` (13 in decimal) for DDS (Data Distribution Service).
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The remaining parts, each separated with a dot, are the node bytes.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Lowercase hexadecimal digits are preferred.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] X.667 requires lowercase on generation, but also requires the uppercase version to be accepted on input.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Since UUIDs are 128-bit numbers, other formats are possible, and occasionally seen, such as decimal digits or binary.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] RFC 4122 registers the "uuid" namespace for URNs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The normal 8-4-4-4-12 format is used for this.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] It is also possible to make an OID out of a UUID, which in turn provides another way to make a URN from it.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The unsigned decimal form of the UUID is prefixed with `2.25`, which represents the `{joint-iso-itu-t(2) uuid(25)}` "arc" within the OID namespace.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This may be further prefixed with `urn:oid:` to make a second form of URN for UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In general, the `uuid` URN is recommended over the `oid` URN.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] A collision occurs when the same UUID is generated more than once and is assigned to different referents.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] In the case of many standard version-1, -2, or -6 UUIDs using unique MAC addresses and/or timestamps, collisions can occur only as a result of error, such as manufacturing problems, skewed clocks, or software bugs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Duplicate UUIDs can also occur due to error with the UUID versions generated using processes such as random number generation or hashing.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] It is important, for example, to have a high-entropy source of randomness when generating version-4 UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] But collisions can also occur without error with such UUIDs, due to chance -- "bad luck".
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The probability of this is normally so small that it can be ignored, and can be computed precisely based on analysis of the birthday problem.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This number would be equivalent to generating 1 billion UUIDs per second for about 86 years.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] A file containing this many UUIDs, at 16 bytes per UUID, would be about 43.4 exabytes (37.7 EiB) -- a file, listing only identifiers, a few orders of magnitude larger than the largest databases currently in existence, which are on the order of 100 PB (e.g.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] If generated according to the standards, duplicate UUIDs are more likely to be the result of bit-flips (a so called Single-event upset) caused by cosmic rays passing through memory or disk storage, than the result of mischance at UUID-generation time.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Thus, the probability to find a duplicate within 103 trillion properly-generated version-4 UUIDs is one in a billion.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Several filesystem types (for example, ext4 and Btrfs) use a UUID to uniquely identify each filesystem to the operating system.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Filesystem userspace tools, most of which are derived from the original implementation by Theodore Ts'o, therefore make use of UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The GUID Partition Table (GPT) uses UUIDs (called there "GUID"s) to identify partitions and partition types.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Unique partition IDs are assigned locally by the operating system.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Partition type IDs are well-known numbers, usually assigned by operating-system or hardware vendors.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] UUIDs are commonly used as a unique key in database tables.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The NEWID function in Microsoft SQL Server version 4 Transact-SQL returns standard random version-4 UUIDs, while the NEWSEQUENTIALID function returns 128-bit identifiers similar to UUIDs which are committed to ascend in sequence until the next system reboot.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The Oracle Database SYS_GUID function does not return a standard GUID, despite the name.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] Instead, it returns a 16-byte 128-bit RAW value based on a host identifier and a process or thread identifier, somewhat similar to a GUID.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] PostgreSQL contains a UUID datatype and can generate most versions of UUIDs through the use of functions from modules.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] MySQL provides a UUID function which generates standard version-1 UUIDs.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] The random nature of standard UUIDs of versions 3, 4, and 5, and the ordering of the fields within standard versions 1 and 2 may create problems with database locality or performance when UUIDs are used as primary keys.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] For example, in 2002 Jimmy Nilsson reported a significant improvement in performance with Microsoft SQL Server when the version-4 UUIDs being used as keys were modified to include a non-random suffix based on system time.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] By reordering and encoding version-1 and -2 UUIDs so that the timestamp comes first, insertion performance loss can be averted.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] This is the rationale for variant 1 (DCE) versions 6 and 7, standardized in RFC 9562.
[src:nanoid-ids/universally-unique-identifier] UEFI and ACPI are examples that use GUID.
